ce:section.ce:para:
MOF-5 is one of the most well-known MOF compounds with three dimensional PCU framework based on {Zn4O} nodes and BDC2− linkers (Fig. 1
                        ). Yan et al. observed that MOF-5 could utilize its large channels to reversibly adsorb and desorb pyridine molecules, achieving naked-eye-observable RTP emission [23]. This interesting result prompts us to further study the possibility of using MOF-5 as a matrix to load other phosphors into its channels to form MOF-based RTP composites. Therefore, firstly MOF-5 was synthesized according to the literature method [60]. Powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) patterns, IR and thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) results are in good agreement with the results reported in the literature [60], indicating that the synthesis was successful (Fig. S1). The solid-state prompt spectrum of MOF-5 was collected at room temperature (Fig. 2
                        ) and only an intense emission peak at 412 nm (λex = 254 nm) can be observed. Comparatively, the delayed spectrum is silent. This means MOF-5 itself will not cause background interference to the delayed spectrum, which is very beneficial to explore RTP emission based on guest phosphors.
